💽 Worker Node Disk Pressure

Your applications are healthy.

Pods are running.

But suddenly the node status changes to:

❌ DiskPressure=True

❌ Pods Failing to Schedule

❌ Node Performance Degradation

Disk pressure is one of the most common infrastructure issues in Kubernetes clusters and can impact the entire node.

Recently, I encountered a worker node where application logs and unused container images gradually consumed all available disk space.

🔍 My troubleshooting approach:

✅ Checked node conditions

✅ Reviewed disk utilization

✅ Investigated kubelet events

✅ Analyzed container log growth

✅ Checked unused Docker/containerd images

✅ Verified ephemeral storage usage

✅ Reviewed monitoring dashboards

✅ Cleaned unnecessary files

🎯 Root Cause:

Large application logs and unused container images consumed most of the node storage.

Once the disk usage crossed the configured threshold, Kubernetes marked the node with DiskPressure and restricted scheduling.

After cleaning old logs and removing unused images, the node returned to a healthy state.

💡 Key Takeaway:

When troubleshooting Disk Pressure, focus on storage consumption trends before the node becomes unhealthy.

Always verify:

• Node disk utilization

• Container image usage

• Log file growth

• Ephemeral storage consumption

• Kubelet events

• Monitoring alerts

• Node conditions

Useful commands:

kubectl describe node <node-name>

df -h

du -sh /var/log/*

crictl images

crictl rmi --prune

Remember:

📌 DiskPressure affects scheduling decisions.

📌 Log growth and image buildup are common causes.

📌 Proactive monitoring prevents production incidents.

Every troubleshooting session improves our understanding of Kubernetes node health and capacity management.
